        <etym xml:lang="en">Goes back to <mentioned xml:lang="ira"><lang/>
            <w type="rec">frīymana-</w></mentioned>, medial participle from <mentioned
            xml:lang="ira"><w type="rec">frī-</w>
            <gloss><q>love</q></gloss>
            <note xml:lang="ru" type="comment">(индоевропейская база <mentioned xml:lang="ine"><w
                  type="rec">pri-</w>, <w type="rec">prəi-</w></mentioned>)</note><note
              xml:lang="en" type="comment">(Indo-European stem <mentioned xml:lang="ine"><w
                  type="rec">pri-</w>, <w type="rec">prəi-</w></mentioned>)</note></mentioned>; cf.
          in terms of derivation <mentioned xml:lang="grc"><lang/>
            <w>φειλάμενος</w>
            <gloss><q>beloved</q></gloss><note xml:lang="ru" type="comment">, мед. причастие от
                <mentioned xml:lang="grc"><w>φιλέω</w>
                <gloss><q>люблю</q></gloss></mentioned></note><note xml:lang="en" type="comment">,
              medial participle of <mentioned xml:lang="grc"><w>φιλέω</w>
                <gloss><q>I love</q></gloss></mentioned></note></mentioned>.<note type="footnote"
              ><hi rendition="#rend_smallcaps">Harmatta</hi> derives this word from <mentioned
              xml:lang="ira"><w type="rec">friya-manah</w>
              <gloss><q>(having) friendly (<mentioned xml:lang="ira"><w type="rec"
                    >friya-</w></mentioned>) spirit (<mentioned xml:lang="ira"><w type="rec"
                      >manah-</w></mentioned>)</q></gloss></mentioned> (<bibl><title type="j">Acta
                Orient. Acad. Scient. Hung.</title>
              <date>1950—1952</date>
              <biblScope>I 302 ff.</biblScope></bibl>). But in this case we would rather expect <w
              type="rec">limon</w>; cf. <ref type="xr" target="#entry_dælīmon"/>, <ref type="xr"
              target="#entry_wælīmon"/>.</note> The sound change <c type="rec">fri-</c> → <c>li-</c>
          is regular: initial <c>f</c> has disappeared before <c>r</c>, as in the preverb <mentioned
            xml:lang="os"><m>ræ-</m></mentioned> from <mentioned xml:lang="ira"><m type="rec"
              >fra-</m></mentioned> or in <ref type="xr" target="#entry_rag"/> from <mentioned
            xml:lang="ira"><w type="rec">frāk-</w></mentioned>, <ref type="xr" target="#entry_rong"
          /> from <mentioned xml:lang="ira"><w type="rec">frānaka-</w></mentioned>; <c>r</c> →
            <c>l</c> before <c>i</c>, as in <ref type="xr" target="#entry_allon"/> from <mentioned
            xml:lang="ira"><w type="rec">aryana</w></mentioned>, <ref type="xr"
            target="#entry_mælyn"/> from <mentioned xml:lang="ira"><w type="rec"
            >marya-</w></mentioned> etc. The stem <mentioned xml:lang="ine"><w type="rec">prī-</w>
            with the meaning <gloss><gloss><q>love</q></gloss>, <gloss><q>be friends
                with</q></gloss> etc.</gloss></mentioned> is well-represented in
          <?oxy_comment_start author="oleg" timestamp="20220525T220756+0300" comment="ideally check all translations against sources"?>Indo-Iranian
          and other Indo-European languages<?oxy_comment_end?>: <mentioned xml:lang="isk"><lang/>
            <w>fri</w>
            <gloss><q>dear</q></gloss>, <gloss><q>good</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned
